text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!Constructed Languages%0a%0a:Author: dennyy%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aAn overview of constructed languages and a few fun examples%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aConstructed languages are languages that are not naturally formed by humans over time, but instead a language that was deliberately created. The reason that people create languages is varied. Some languages were created to serve as an universal language. Others were created to facilitate scientific experiments or philosophical discussions. Creating languages can also help someone learn about linguistics. Finally, some people just find it to be a fun hobby.%0a%0aExamples:%0a%0aEsperanto:%0aEsperanto is, according to many, the most successful constructed language. Created in 1887 for the purpose of being used as a lingua franca, it is largely derived from other European languages. Some estimates place the number of Esperanto speakers at 100,000, and there are even some native speakers(3). It also has a course on Duolingo.%0a%0aKlingon:%0aKlingon is an artificial language spoken by the fictional alien race of the same name in Star Trek. It has been a commercial success, with a dictionary having sold 300,000 copies(2). It has a course on Duolingo, for some reason.%0a%0aIthkuil:%0aIthkuil is a constructed language made with the goal of allowing the speaker to communicate with extreme detail and with barely an ambiguity, while using as few  sounds as possible. To achieve this, it has 58 phonemes(English has 42), and the results are stunning. For example, "Aukkras  êqutta  ogvëuļa  tnou’elkwa  pal-lši  augwaikštülnàmbu" translates to "An imaginary representation of a nude woman in the midst of descending a staircase in a step-by-step series of tightly-integrated ambulatory bodily movements which combine into a three-dimensional wake behind her, forming a timeless, emergent whole to be considered intellectually, emotionally and aesthetically."(4) It should not be a surprise that Ithkuil was not created with the intention of actually being spoken.%0a%0aI dare the reader to get hired at Duolingo and make Ithkuil a course.%0a%0aToki Pona:%0aIn stark contrast to Ithkuil, Toki Pona is a language intended to be as simple as possible, and highly subject to interpretation. It has just 137 essential words(6), but still functions as a language. As such, it only takes about 30 hours to master(5).%0a%0a(1)https://www.merriam-webster.com/words-at-play/conlang-meaning-origin%0a(2)https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2012/12/24/utopian-for-beginners%0a(3)https://www.britannica.com/topic/Esperanto%0a(4)http://ithkuil.net/texts.html%0a(5)https://www.businessinsider.com/the-worlds-smallest-language-has-only-100-words-and-you-can-say-almost-anything-2015-7%0a(6)https://tokipona.org/%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 221205-185802-667780#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Constructed Languages in the work of J.R.R. Tolkien %0a-> - nickb%0a-> [-05.12.2022 - 10:58-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221205-185802-667780 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aConstructed languages have been built for decades if not centuries, and one if the most famous inventors of such languages is J.R.R. Tolkien. Tolkien was a British writer famous for The Lord of the Rings, a fantasy epic. Within his world several languages other than English are spoken and written. While many exist as shells of languages, some are fully realized constructed languages. Quenya, for example, is a language spoken by elves, which shares many traits with Finnish. Tolkien's addition to the world of constructed languages are difficult to overstate, as he was one of the first authors to invent a language solely for the purpose of his books. %0a%0aSource:%0ahttps://tolkiengateway.net/wiki/Languages%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221205-185802-667780#%0a#foxbegin 221207-213025-893790#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Lojban, another constructed language %0a-> - cassidy%0a-> [-07.12.2022 - 13:30-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221207-213025-893790 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aAnother successful conlang (constructed language) out there is Lojban, created by the Logical Language Group. The primary feature of the language is its hope to remove all ambiguity from human communication. Lojban can be uniquely "parsed" much like a programming language. Computers were integral to Logban's construction; its root words were algorithmically determined by searching for common sound patterns in Mandarin, English, Hindi, Spanish, Russian, and Arabic words.%0a%0aIt was initially created as a test of the Sapir-Whorf hypothesis, which questions to what extent one's language determines their thoughts. Today, many linguists no longer believe in linguistic determinism, but Lojban itself continues to exist outside of that space with interesting language research implications and a niche following of speakers.%0a%0aSources:%0a[1] https://tiki.lojban.org/Lojban%0a[2] https://lojban.io/resources/%0a[3] https://lojban.github.io/cll/4/14/%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221207-213025-893790#%0a#foxbegin 221209-185231-850520#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Kerch, a constructed writing system %0a-> - jackagui%0a-> [-09.12.2022 - 10:52-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221209-185231-850520 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aKerch is a constructed language with its own writing system, used in the Six of Crows and the Shadow and Bone series. It was created by David J. Peterson, who also created the languages used in Game of Thrones and many other fictional pieces of media. However, it is not a fully-fledged language, only some words are known, though of the words known there is a clear Dutch influence, with some of the words even remaining unchanged. However, it does still have a complete writing system, although all of the text we read in the writing system is written in the language of English. In this writing system, "ch" is considered a single symbol. This is not the case for English, though I do know that it used to be considered a letter in Spanish.%0a%0aInteresting to note about it is that the symbol for vowels is attached to the preceding consonant symbol, with a couple exceptions. If there is no preceding consonant, a separate 'base' symbol is used. As well, for certain combinations of two vowels in a row, rather than writing them out separately, a single symbol is used. It's an interesting departure from English orthography, and some examples are below:%0a%0aFor example, the word "like" would use two symbols, one for "li" and one for "ke", where the symbol for "li" is the symbol for "i" attached to the right side of the symbol for "l", and the symbol for "ke" is constructed similarly. Likewise, the symbol for "look" would also use two symbols, one for "loo" and one for "k", where the symbol for "loo" would be the symbol for "oo" (which looks similar to the symbol for "o") attached to the right side of the symbol for "l"%0a%0aI have a more detailed explanation of the writing system here, that includes all of the symbols as well as examples of written words: https://docs.google.com/document/d/11PiRD5xvh5g9An_erDYcCCwwVEAiOYN1gCpTAITvDVI/edit?usp=sharing%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221209-185231-850520#%0a#foxbegin 221210-002206-133080#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Some interesting Ithkuil designs %0a-> - ziqiliu%0a-> [-09.12.2022 - 16:22-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221210-002206-133080 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aTypology: Ithkuil is a "primarily agglutinative and secondarily synthetic language," as the words are formed by linearly appending affixes to the stems, but the affixes themselves are highly synthetic. %0a%0aMorphology: Ithkuil does not distinguish between verb and noun, because "Ithkuil morpho-semantics does not see nouns and verbs as being cognitively distinct from one another, but rather as complementary manifestations of ideas existing in a common underlying semantic continuum whose components are space and time." What is known as verb and noun part-of-speeches in Western languages are called "formative" in Ithkuil. %0a%0aOrthography: Ithkuil sentences are written in a zig-zag way. The first sentence is written left-to-right, and the second right-to-left, and the third back to left-to-right and so on. %0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221210-002206-133080#%0a#foxbegin 221210-035808-161910#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Fictional Languages %0a-> - anuj%0a-> [-09.12.2022 - 19:58-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221210-035808-161910 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aMany creative works make use of constructed languages to build an immersive world. These works range from literary works like Tolkien's Lord of the Rings to those made for films and TV shows like Star War's Huttese and Game of Throne's Dothraki.%0a%0aDespite all of these examples, it is well understood that creating languages is hard, so why do it for a fictional world. Well most creative works don't need one, in most sci-fi or fantasy works one can get around this by simply stating that non-native languages simply seem like gibberish to the characters and later provide a method of instantaneous translation. One franchise where this method is most often seen is the DC universe which has an incredibly diverse cast spanning multiple galaxies and universes. Despite this the question of languages is almost never encountered throughout the franchise and when it is it usually gets quickly brushed over with some method of universal translation. That's not to say that this is not necessarily immersive, its just one way of doing things. %0a%0aWell if this is all true then why do people make new languages just for fictional books. Well some people are just really dedicated. For example J.R.R. Tolkien actually created over 15 different languages and dialects spoken among different creatures and populations. This is certainly more a departure from the norm. We actually have started to see this constructed languages most commonly in TV series. In a medium like television where you are able to hear what is being said rather than reading it these languages become far more effective because it forces you to try and understand what is being said through the emotions of the speaker rather than the actual words.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221210-035808-161910#%0a#foxbegin 221210-041026-26060#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Korean Hangul Writing System %0a-> - nsodhi%0a-> [-09.12.2022 - 20:10-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221210-041026-26060 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aMany centuries ago, the Korean language used a writing system known as Hanja. This system was based on Chinese and was very complex, but it was the natural writing system that had evolved over time. Then, in the fifteenth century, King Sejong the Great decided to construct his own writing system for the language, attempting to make it more phonetic and simple in hopes to raise literacy rates. The script took several more centuries to fully catch on, but nowadays it is the official writing system of Korea. One neat fact about the script is that the consonants are based on the shape of the tongue while uttering the sound! (Think of the place of articulation on the IPA chart. This is quite impressive for a system created nearly 600 years ago.)%0a%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hanja %0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hangul %0ahttps://blog.duolingo.com/hangeul-fun-facts/ %0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221210-041026-26060#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:Section: B:)%0a(:Category: Varia:)%0a(:Title: Constructed Languages:)
