diff:1670645426:1670644688:=170,189d169%0a%3c #foxbegin 221210-041026-26060#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Korean Hangul Writing System %0a%3c -> - nsodhi%0a%3c -> [-09.12.2022 - 20:10-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221210-041026-26060 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Many centuries ago, the Korean language used a writing system known as Hanja. This system was based on Chinese and was very complex, but it was the natural writing system that had evolved over time. Then, in the fifteenth century, King Sejong the Great decided to construct his own writing system for the language, attempting to make it more phonetic and simple in hopes to raise literacy rates. The script took several more centuries to fully catch on, but nowadays it is the official writing system of Korea. One neat fact about the script is that the consonants are based on the shape of the tongue while uttering the sound! (Think of the place of articulation on the IPA chart. This is quite impressive for a system created nearly 600 years ago.)%0a%3c %0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hanja %0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hangul %0a%3c https://blog.duolingo.com/hangeul-fun-facts/ %0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221210-041026-26060#%0a
