diff:1670117072:1670117072:=1,105d0%0a%3c (:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0a%3c Status: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!{$:Category}]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Constructed Languages%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: dennyy%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c An overview of constructed languages and a few fun examples%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Constructed languages are languages that are not naturally formed by humans over time, but instead a language that was deliberately created. The reason that people create languages is varied. Some languages were created to serve as an universal language. Others were created to facilitate scientific experiments or philosophical discussions. Creating languages can also help someone learn about linguistics. Finally, some people just find it to be a fun hobby.%0a%3c %0a%3c Examples:%0a%3c %0a%3c Esperanto:%0a%3c Esperanto is, according to many, the most successful constructed language. Created in 1887 for the purpose of being used as a lingua franca, it is largely derived from other European languages. Some estimates place the number of Esperanto speakers at 100,000, and there are even some native speakers(3). It also has a course on Duolingo.%0a%3c %0a%3c Klingon:%0a%3c Klingon is an artificial language spoken by the fictional alien race of the same name in Star Trek. It has been a commercial success, with a dictionary having sold 300,000 copies(2). It has a course on Duolingo, for some reason.%0a%3c %0a%3c Ithkuil:%0a%3c Ithkuil is a constructed language made with the goal of allowing the speaker to communicate with extreme detail and with barely an ambiguity, while using as few  sounds as possible. To achieve this, it has 58 phonemes(English has 42), and the results are stunning. For example, "Aukkras  êqutta  ogvëuļa  tnou’elkwa  pal-lši  augwaikštülnàmbu" translates to "An imaginary representation of a nude woman in the midst of descending a staircase in a step-by-step series of tightly-integrated ambulatory bodily movements which combine into a three-dimensional wake behind her, forming a timeless, emergent whole to be considered intellectually, emotionally and aesthetically."(4) It should not be a surprise that Ithkuil was not created with the intention of actually being spoken.%0a%3c %0a%3c I dare the reader to get hired at Duolingo and make Ithkuil a course.%0a%3c %0a%3c Toki Pona:%0a%3c In stark contrast to Ithkuil, Toki Pona is a language intended to be as simple as possible, and highly subject to interpretation. It has just 137 essential words(6), but still functions as a language. As such, it only takes about 30 hours to master(5).%0a%3c %0a%3c (1)https://www.merriam-webster.com/words-at-play/conlang-meaning-origin%0a%3c (2)https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2012/12/24/utopian-for-beginners%0a%3c (3)https://www.britannica.com/topic/Esperanto%0a%3c (4)http://ithkuil.net/texts.html%0a%3c (5)https://www.businessinsider.com/the-worlds-smallest-language-has-only-100-words-and-you-can-say-almost-anything-2015-7%0a%3c (6)https://tokipona.org/%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c You must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a%3c !!Change article category%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:Section: B:)%0a%3c (:Category: Varia:)%0a%3c (:Title: Constructed Languages:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
